text:
sexual harassment and being jabbed by dirty syringes are just some of the hazards commercial laundromat workers can face on a daily basis. the commercial laundromat industry services linens for hotels, hospitals and restaurants, and according to investigative reporter, @anniehylton, it is riddled with poor and dangerous working conditions. 
after a 6-month long investigation, annie joined @bradshowlive to share her findings, all published in her article “dirty laundry” for @dissentmag. 
there is a “lack of basic safety equipment and training,” annie told @bernstein_brad on @bradshowlive. “the women who i profiled in the piece, told me that they didn’t even have gloves to wear, so when they were dealing with laundry, people would get poked by syringes and their fingers would start bleeding.” not only are the workers, many of them immigrant women, exposed to unsafe conditions, but sexual harassment also lurks many facilities. “one woman who i spoke to was sexually harassed for months and months and months by her manager,” annie said. 
the article also touches upon a lawsuit that was filed by eight women. as a result, monetary settlement and sexual harassment training came to a head, but also, retaliation. “a number of the women faced retaliation, like lowered hours and more laborious work,” she described of the management's response to the lawsuit. “if you are experiencing something like this, like the women who i talk about in this piece, i know it’s difficult and scary,” she noted on @bradshowlive. “but you need to tell somebody, and you need to get help, because you don’t deserve this. there are rights in this country, even if people tell you otherwise.” check out the full interview, and watch @bradshowlive with @bernstein_brad monday through friday from 5:30-7:30 p.m. est. on youtube (link in bio). 📸 1 cred: sara hylton 📸 2 : reporting texas 📸3: voices of ny 📸 4: @dissentmag 📸 5: #twitter

text:
💋mujer, tú tambien puedes!👧
.
.
aunque a muchas mujeres nos asuste la idea, viajar sola puede ser una gran experiencia para ti. cada vez más mujeres se animan a viajar solas.
.
según estadísticas de migración colombia, 194.127 mujeres hicieron trámite de salida del país en el pasado mes de enero 2018 (lo que corresponde al 52 por ciento del total), mientras que al país en el primer mes del año ingresaron 89.469 extranjeras, casi la mitad del total de los hombres.
.
no tengas miedo de emprender una aventura. pero antes ten en cuenta estas claves...
.
🔹️tener información de buena fuente antes de viajar.
.
🔹️lleva en tu maleta ropa únicamente para ti. (solemos encartarnos con más de lo que necesitamos 🙈)
.
🔹️cuenta con un seguro de viaje y un botiquín apropiado. (llevando cositas básicas y no olvides las recetas médicas, en la mayoría de paises te piden formula médica)
.
🔹️no te confíes de la gente y sé precavida. (es triste pero como dice mi mamá: "caras vemos... corazones no sabemos")
.
🔹️sé tú misma, pero con prudencia.
.
🔹️lleva ropa con la que te sientas cómoda. (lo más práctica chicas! no vamos para el fashion week de paris!)
.
🔹️lleva un celular siempre contigo. (y por el amor de dios! siempre lleva contigo powers bank para que tengas batería🔋)
.
🔹️si sales de noche, movilízate en taxi en lugares reconocidos ó camina por sitios públicos. .
🔹️revisa tus mapas antes de salir. (es rico y casi aventurero perderse entre las calles... pero aja, es mejor ir con puntos claros para no terminar más perdida que la mamá del chavo 😂)
.
🔹️pregunta y aprende sobre tus destinos de viaje. (experiencias previas podrán aterrizarte más a la realidad del destino).
.
.
y aunque todas estas recomendaciones no deberían el deber - ser, porque día a día luchamos por nuestros derechos como mujeres, no sobra decirte que el mundo nos espera pero hay que tener responsabilidad y conciencia de la sociedad en la que vivimos.
.
.
.
te animas?.. comentame a dónde te gustaría viajar sola ⬇️
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#travelgirl #empowergirls #shetravels #travelerslife #borntotravel #igerscolombia #viajerosinexcusas #mujeresviajeras #metoo #wanderlust #travel #graffiti

text:
beliefs are masks we wear given by our parents, friends, educational institutions, churches, governments, social surroundings and they construct a reality by which most (if not all) of our decisions are made.
**
beliefs create our truths, they create how we perceive ourselves, they create limitations by which we are willing to "believe". **
beliefs limit the potentiality of creation and become subconscious inhibitors of limitless possibilities and potentials.
**
i believe to reach a place of untethered freedom and creation we must be willing to accept that the purpose of "belief" is to create a launching point by which we perceive from,not to create a place to judge perception from.
**
believe it or not - you wear many masks, a question which deserves answering is "who's mask are you wearing" **

text:
o leite do peito é fraco 😒
.
só o leite do peito não sustenta,
.
o leite é fraco,
.
você tem que dar uma água,
.
tem que dar chazinho,
.
tem que intercalar com a fórmula,
.
incrível como as pessoas ficam falando estas frases...
mas esse mito do leite fraco, muitas vezes está associado ao excessivo choro do bebê, que parece querer mamar a toda hora (“está com fome porque não se sente alimentado”).
as mães precisam ter consciência – e manter a calma nessa fase – de que nos primeiros meses o choro é a única forma de comunicação da criança. o bebê quer mamar a toda hora porque ele está aprendendo a fazer isso. ele se cansa, para, dorme e como não mamou tudo o que podia, pede novamente, abrindo o berreiro. é assim mesmo e muda depois de algum tempo. tempo suficiente para ele aprender a dinâmica do mamar.
.
.
.
cada pessoa tem uma opinião, algumas realmente precisam introduzir algo a mais para seu bebê, mas por aqui eu quero utilizar o leite materno exclusivamente até os 6 meses 😍🍼
.
.

text:
the moment you get lost in all the redness♦️♦️♦️
。
do you pay attention to the colors around you?
。
do you know their meaning?
。
can you feel how they affect your mood?♥️♥️♥️
。
on an emotional level, red color carries the energy of anger. what do you do with anger? do you blow up? do you repress it?
do you become depressed?
depression often is a sign of internalized anger❗️learning how to get in touch with your anger and transform it is an important step towards your inner balance🙏
。
ancient chinese philosophy called feng shui talks about it in detail as well as indian wisdom of ayurveda🔥🔥🔥
。
what is your emotion connected with red⁉️🛑

si pinchas en este enlace y tiras hacia abajo un poquito, verás cómo me presenta la editorial mito: https://mitoeditorial.blogspot.com/p/autor-invitado.html 👋😹👍🐩💫
puedes leer artículos míos en diario alhaurín y en 101 málaga, así como en las revistas culturales guatiní (miami) y mimeógrafo (méxico). también me presentaron en la ventana del arte (la guía más completa sobre exposiciones en españa) y en webs y blogs como: munduky y repoelas (ambas españolas) y, en inglés, en art reveal magazine https://go.shr.lc/2u3tk4e 🍹🎻🦄💂 mis novelas llegan a cualquier lugar 🗺 desde: 
my novels arrive everywhere from

http://www.bubok.es/autores/bokusu

puedes pinchar el enlace en mi perfil.
verás que están en papel; que puedes leer las primeras páginas, algunas críticas y más... la 1ª también en formato digital. son para mayores de 18 años.

you can click the link in my profile. you'll see they are in paper, you can read the first pages, some critics and more... the first one is also for ebook, your computer, etc. they are for adults. 😘

puedes seguirme también en youtube, fb (2 perfiles, uno más usado que el otro, y una página de autora), en twitter y soundcloud (otros 2 perfiles, uno de ellos con más de 30 grabaciones en español, inglés y francés macarrónico)

text:
did they know? 
did they know how much they were taking away from me? 
did they know that their actions would bear such consequences for me?
did they know that they were breaking a human being?

did they know? 
that for years i wouldn’t understand that what they did was wrong? 
that every day i foolishly thought that it was my fault? 
that i was drowning in shame because of their uncontrolled want?

did they know?
that, on some days, i would convince myself that it was all in my head? 
that those unwelcome touches were all lies i to myself fed? 
that the liquid that trickled down my thighs wasn’t red?

do they know?
that they made all men alike predators in my eyes? 
that i find it impossible to place my trust in their lies? 
that for their wrongs against a little girl, a young woman still cries?

do they know? 
that what i wish for those vermin is not an easy death?
that they deserve to feel the full weight of what they did?
that i doubt that they are human enough to feel something akin to guilt?

stanzas from questions on my mind #metoo
©2018 faiza sahar

- representative romero is another one of our speakers this saturday! angela romero has always had a passion to serve. growing up in tooele, utah, angela was raised by her grandparents. their dedication to raising a hard-working, well-educated woman inspired her to pursue college, graduating with a bachelor’s degree in political science and a master’s degree in public administration from the university of utah. in 2012, she won election to represent house district 26 at the utah state legislature. in 2018, she was elected by her colleagues to serve as the house democratic assistant whip.
with almost two decades of public service, angela oversees community programs and initiatives in the division of youth and family programs, including supervising the youthcity government program. at the state legislature, she champions issues that include victim’s rights, sexual assault and domestic violence prevention. in addition to her professional career and legislative duties, angela currently serves as the national hispanic caucus of state legislator’s vice president. she also serves on the prevent child abuse utah board of directors, utah’s rape kit processing work group, friends for sight board of directors, salt lake acting company board of directors, and is the national foundation for women legislator’s utah state director. we are so excited to hear her speak!
.

text:
no matter how many books you read or how many degrees you have, i think there will always be an ounce of you that will never truly “get” how narcissists and psychopaths can treat people with such unconscionable disrespect.
.
you can learn why they are the way they are and you can learn how they operate. you can comprehend and you can sympathize. but i don’t think most of us will ever truly understand them.
.
that can be frustrating as hell and it can lead you down some dangerous rabbit holes searching for answers you’ll never find. my advice is to learn the basics (a book or two ought to do it in the beginning) then turn inward to your healing; owning and loving that frustration. don’t allow that frustration to swell into contempt. instead, own it and embrace it as the exact quality that makes you a beautiful human being. 💛🦋

text:
gillette’s new ad “the best a man can be”, that questioned its own tagline “the best a man can get” has wreaked havoc on the internet since it’s release. as of 18th january 2019, the ad stands at 19m views with around 500k likes and a whopping 970k dislikes with more than 400k comments. the ad analyses how toxic masculinity spins the narrative of bullying, sexual harassment, objectification of women and mansplaining. it attempts to redefine real manliness so that boys find better role models in the men they look up to.
however, apparently, this “unnecessary misandrist moral lecture” hasn’t gone very well with our “masculine” viewers. as the ad challenges the notions of “boys will be boys” and holding men accountable for their actions, men have flooded the internet with angry grunts of “let boys be” and “boycott gillette” - maybe because men aren’t used to hearing what is right and what is wrong, maybe because they think that real men have the authority to do whatever they want and get away with it and maybe because being a decent human being threatens their fragile male ego.

the gillette ad is another beautiful example where men pant #notallmen and start whataboutism over women. even worse, the hashtag #letboysbe is a dangerous call to protect toxic masculinity. it is about reinforcing gender stereotypes of men being authoritative and dominating and considering kind, compassionate ones as less of a man. just looking at the comments section illustrates so much toxic masculinity in action *rolls eyes*.
it is horrific that in spite of such strong women empowerment movements and with the ongoing #metoo wave, something as subtle as a razor ad, that talks about doing away with toxic masculinity, has shattered the fragile male ego to the extent of being boycotted. the ad is being misinterpreted as anti-men, just like the whole feminism wave – evident of the facts that not being a bully is anti-men, not harassing women is anti-men or not being a jerk is anti-men. in short, being human is being anti-men *slow claps*. the irrational hate and anger of men, towards something that merely asks them to not be awful humans, immediately justifies the very existence of this ad.

text:
facing populist assault, global elites regroup in davos:
⠀⠀⠀
as the world’s financial and political elites convene here in the swiss alps for the world economic forum, their vision of ever-closer commercial and political ties is under attack — and the economic outlook is darkening.
⠀⠀⠀
britain’s political system has been thrown into chaos as the country negotiates a messy divorce from the european union.
⠀⠀⠀
under president donald trump, the united states is imposing trade sanctions on friend and foe alike, and the government is paralyzed by a partial shutdown over immigration policy that forced trump and a high-level u.s. delegation to cancel the trip to davos.
⠀⠀⠀
a year after getting a standing ovation from the elites at davos, french president emmanuel macron is sinking in the polls as he contends with “yellow vest” protesters who have taken to the streets to call for higher wages and fairer pensions. nationalist political movements are gaining strength across europe.
⠀⠀⠀
and the economic backdrop is worrying: experts are downgrading their forecasts for global growth this year amid rising interest rates and tensions over trade.
name: The Right Brothers Post
tweet_full:
facing populist assault, global elites regroup in davos:
⠀⠀⠀
as the world’s ficial and political elites convene here in the swiss alps for the world economic forum, their vision of ever-closer commercial and political ties is under attack — and the economic outlook is darkening.
⠀⠀⠀
britain’s political system has been thrown into chaos as the country negotiates a messy divorce from the european union.
⠀⠀⠀
under president donald trump, the united states is imposing trade sanctions on friend and foe alike, and the government is paralyzed by a partial shutdown over immigration policy that forced trump and a high-level u.s. delegation to cancel the trip to davos.
⠀⠀⠀
a year after getting a standing ovation from the elites at davos, french president emmanuel macron is sinking in the polls as he contends with “yellow vest” protesters who have taken to the streets to call for higher wages and fairer pensions. nationalist political movements are gaining strength across europe.
⠀⠀⠀
and the economic backdrop is worrying: experts are downgrading their forecasts for global growth this year amid rising interest rates and tensions over trade.

text:
¡quedan las últimas 100 historias! el tiempo ha pasado muy deprisa, parece que fue ayer cuando la idea de este proyecto daba vueltas en mi cabeza. pero quiero deciros que este proyecto no solo son las 265 historias que se han publicado hasta ahora, son todas las que me pedís que publique en anónimo, las que me pedís consejo, las que me animáis, las que comentáis cada día, las que compartís y difundís. sois todas y cada una, este proyecto tiene un pequeño espacio aquí gracias a vosotras, gracias a vuestra voz. siento si tardo en contestar pero a diario me llegan más de 100 mensajes (y no exagero) por lo que requiere mucho tiempo para leer, contestar y publicar. me encantaría daros voz a todas, ójala pudiera y ójala no tuviera que hacerlo. me pone triste leer todas vuestras historias, pero a la vez me da fuerza para continuar porque queda mucho por lograr.

quedan 100 historias para completar las primeras 365, pero os aseguro que esto solo ha empezado. una vez más gracias. #soymujer365

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
a year and one day ago, i sat in my living room in tears of rage making a sign, as i watched a former student confront our mutual abuser in court. 
a year ago today i woke up, and wrote a personal statement of my own to be read for the judge and for the world. 
i took my sign, met strangers at panera and marched. it was the first time i physically spoke about my abuse to strangers. when two individuals dressed in spartan gear came up to me, i looked them square in the eyes and told them michigan state needed to be held accountable for their lack of action in preventing my abuse. up until that point, i had never felt more empowered. 
a year ago today, my new friend miguel took this picture of me, and it was shared by the huff post, by olympians, and by my sister survivors. 
it has been a year of ups and downs, years of rage, tears anxiety, tears of sadness and tears of happiness. 
but i will not rest and i will keep marching until the day institutions are held accountable for the sexual violence that occurs under their watch. i will keep marching for every victim who feels they are unheard. 
i see you, i hear you, i believe you. .
.
.
#metoo #metoomsu #womensmarch2018 #womensmarchchi #survivor #believewomen

text:
i made a decision to stop hiding.
i’m sorry for not showing up sooner.
i didn’t want to say who i really was.
i felt scared to embrace the depth of myself. how much wisdom and power i had inside of me. how dark and unheard of my experience has been.
i tried for so long to keep it suppressed and hidden. i was even willing to bury it under more pain and suffering, struggle and chaos. just to avoid getting to the core of it and really surrendering, to the truth, my truth.
i began to write my story, the real one, as it is, how i felt it, how i see it.
i finally had the willingness to write it, to sit with it, to own it, to become it, to embrace it.
and it took a lot of strength. so much strength that i didn’t know i had in me.
i didn’t want to be that person, i didn’t want to be this person.
i was avoiding it for so long, and i was trying to be and do anything but what was really the heart of the matter, why i was really here and what message i had to share.
the story that would change the world and change lives — my story.
i hid under the fear that maybe it wouldn’t matter to anyone, that maybe no one would care and it wasn’t worthwhile.
but that was a big fat lie. of course this mattered, of course people would care, of course this would help people.
it was my own sabotaging ways that were the problem blocking me, not the dismissal of others.
in fact, i could feel people waiting for me to step forward with this medicine, with my truth, with the truth of who i really was.
the truth about who i was before the event, who i was after the event, and who i am now.
i’m sorry, but i had to come home to my story, first.
i had to come to terms with my truth first, before i was ready to share it. before i was ready to actually be here with you, to be here as the real me, the one who went through the trauma, the one who suffered and survived. the one who was hidden behind self-betrayal and abandonment, disguised as many other distracting things.
i wasn’t allowed to step forward until now. fear held me back, in a cage. but i broke free.
i finally broke free.
it took my whole heart to get here.
yeah, i was scared that my family would read about what i was up to.
contd below ❤️

text:
day four, final day of installation!
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

.
altras geld up very well. very pleased with them.
.

lamentable hecho sucedido la noche de ayer en #ibarra, a la luz pública y con la policía nacional presente. el conviviente de #diana, de nacionalidad venezolana, la mantuvo de rehén (detalles en desarrollo), amenazándola con un cuchillo. pedía se le abra camino para poder fugarse a #quito. durante 90 minutos amenazó con asesinarla y finalmente lo hizo (acto quedó grabado por los presentes que pedían asesinarlo). la multitud trató de hacer justicia por su cuenta y la policía lanzó gas lacrimógeno para calmar a las personas enardecidas por tan sangriento desenlace. ¿por qué la negociación falló? ¿por qué la policía no logró evitar el asesinato de diana? ¿por qué la policía no actuó de forma diferente sabiendo que una vida corría riesgo inminente? otro #femicidio se agrega a la triste lista de crímenes por violencia de género en lo que va del 2019.
#niunamenos #metoo #nomasviolenciadegenero

text:
un libro da leggere, sottolineare, e regalare. uno di quei testi in cui passare dal pianto alla risata nel giro di poche righe. una voce che da modo al femminismo gioioso di esser condiviso e abbracciato, in cui si chiede a donne e uomini di fanne parte. si parla di corpo, linguaggio e di tutte quelle pratiche per diventare attive di un movimento essenziale. per liberarci dagli stereotipi che vede le femministe incazzate e rabbiose ma che vuole coinvolgere tutti, senza esclusione di genere, sesso e orientamento. un libro per diffondere un femminismo fuori dalle porte degli addetti ai lavori, di ispirazione e soprattutto di grandi consigli pratici.
insomma, rimbocchiamoci le mani e facciamo tutti la nostra parte. ogni giorno, per creare un cultura femminista utile a tutti. donne e uomini compresi. .
.
.

text:
the penn (students newspaper at university of pennyslvania) wrote: "clothing is apparently a big deal in this world of sexual harassment and assault. but it shouldn't be. focusing so much on a person’s dress is not only taking away from his or her experiences, but it also continues the idea that victims are at fault for their circumstances." ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
"the concept that women should avoid dressing “like sluts” in order not to be victimized is nothing new. women begin to receive this message from a young age. teens — even children,  are sexualized for everything from their bare shoulders to their “too tight” pants." ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
i try to talk about this topic as much as i can. it is uncomfortable because there will always be disagreements, and the reason behind those disagreements is because it has been ingrained in our brains to sexualize women's bodies. one of the clearest examples is when people label mothers breastfeeding in public as "inappropriate" (even though they're feeding their babies, nothing sexual). the public sees women's breasts, and bodies,  as sexual objects. it is uncomfortable to talk about but change begins by talking about these uncomfortable things with friends, family and your social media followers— in person and/ or through social media posts.  who knows, it might give people a different perspective? ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
unfortunately there are still people who think that we should teach victims — which are mostly women , — how to dress properly instead of teaching rapists to not rape.  that should change. we should teach our sons to be a proper human being and the importance of consent. if you are a victim of rape, it is not your fault.  i stand with you. i encourage you to read this article by @the.independent about the display of rape victims outfits. it is eye opening to show us that even people wearing socially labelled as "appropriate outfits" are victims. please also read the jakarta post article about the importance of psychological help for rape survivors. both links are in bio. ⁣⁣
#timesup #metoo

text:
one of my favorite experiences this past trip was facilitating a workshop in samut prakan with migrant mothers and children from myanmar. under dhamma theatre west and ruth pongstapgone, the in us, between us, around us: creativity workshop for growing the environment of mother and child was designed.

the workshop was created to inspire awareness of the relationship between mother and child, to grow the strength of that relationship through creativity and imagination. the workshop aimed to provide a safe space in which to explore the use of movement, music and breath as way for children and mothers to create environments together. 
visual art activities, including portrait making photography, offered mothers and children a new way to see and express their feelings for each other. a special thank you to pawaluk suraswadi for her help and knowledge.

i cannot wait to share all i have learned from my mentors and the communities. i am currently finishing up a research blog covering the first two phases of my learning under ajahn pongstaphone! i hope to share it with everyone soon💕

text:
two years ago i marched alone.  and was inspired and lit up by the families, men and sense of possibility.  we weren’t marching against, we were marching for. 
yesterday, i got to march with my mountain family- 3 generations together.  marching for inclusion, love and a system that works. 
my revolution starts in this body.  the body that has healed from self abuse, physical abuse, domestic violence and sexual abuse. it may start in the body but with generations before and after us, the next generation i spend my time and attention and intention with, won’t have to say, #metoo. 
this pink wave is only beginning.

text:
i went to church this morning with so many questions in my head, 😳🧐🤓??????????? praying so hard i almost passed out. 
the pastor tony spoke about it all but most importantly he spoke about respect, honor and dignity. 
men and women should be equal but men will lead, serve, protect and note 📝 this ......... never ever like in ever speak ill about their partners to others or disrespect them when disagreeing on some matters. they will open the car door, they will do the little things, not because us women are weak, but because we are daughters of a king, our father in heaven expects the men in our lives to honor, love and protect us, we are his daughters. men should be loyal and faithful al the time. they must stay honest and kind. and this was the best part .... giggle🤣🤣🤣🤣 that if you don’t obey what the bible say that it is possible that someone’s almighty hands will “bless you” in an uncomfortable way. i just love the truth at this church. 
women will care and respect equally back, with dignity, kindness, honesty and love. we look after the men that god send us. it’s not that we are slaves. we nurture, we love, we protect, we trust. we give back in other forms 
#respect #dignity #kindness #love #sunday #truth #trust #protect #whatgoesaroundcomesaround #faith #metoo #faithful #honesty #wife #husband

text:
the woman facing us walked backwards, drumming, swaying to the beat, leading, calling the rhythms, looking super joyful. she really inspired me. 🥁
my friend @kellybreauxfitness , is an amazing drummer and always brings her drum to the gatherings, marches, rallies, protests, and yesterday was no different. she fits right in with this talented group.
🥁
i, on the other hand, have very little experience on the drum, but i brought my little jembe anyway. it's really hard to drum, walk, keep anything more complicated than a 1,2,3,4 beat (for me, at least), and sway in synch with a group. i am truly grateful i was included.
🥁
inclusion. the big take away message from this year's women's march. we are battling against an administration hell bent on dividing, separating, excluding, shaming, putting up walls. i really appreciate all of those who came to the  stage and spoke about community, inclusion, and acceptance.
🥁

text:
[read this] yesterday, at the end of the march, i stood under an awning to listen to our mayor speak. at that moment, a woman nearby saw my sign, looked at me with compassion and said a simple, “yes.” she then said, “can i give you a hug?” (and of course i obliged!) as she hugged me, she whispered in my ear, “me too.” at that moment, #metoo was not a hashtag or a social media phenomenon. it was a real pain being released by the understanding between two strangers. it was a beautiful moment. it was healing. it’s #whyimarch. 
photo by @deiaenna ❤️

text:
rani mehra was true representation of an indian girl in middle-class household, who is mostly vulnerable, shy, soft-spoken, under-confident, but also wishes good for people surrounding her. and although she never spoke about it, but she aversed being controlled by others. she enjoyed her freedom to drink and dance at her will, wear whatever she felt like, visit new places and encounter new adventures.
she loved to cook for others, easily trusted people around her, and her love was extremely passionate. and although shy, she was not an introvert and enjoyed dancing with a group or when she was drunk. in fact, she loved having fun with people whenever she had an opportunity. her extroversion and inner thoughts could be clearly seen when she was drunk.
further, she always tried to put her brave face on even during troublesome situations, but had no problem in breaking down into tears when she was free and her emotions always emerged in her mother tongue.
rani was extremely friendly in her etiquettes and hardly over-thought about situations or her decisions, letting things flow smoothly. and whenever proven wrong, she was quick to learn from her mistakes and made sure to never repeat the same.
rani was relatable for some and motivational for others, but had connect with every indian girl.

ps: indians sab cheez mein best hai. kissing mein bhi indians hi best hai! kabhi emraan hashmi ka naam nahi suna?

pps: kangana ranaut secured national and filmfare awards for best actress for her portrayal of rani mehra, and given its wide appeal and connection with indian society, the film is being remade in tamil, telugu, kannada and malayalam.

text: so yet again last night i was sexually harassed, groped, manipulated, coerced until i fought back & said hell to the no!! and yes you could all blame me for being stupid enough or trusting enough to go have a drink with a seemingly trustworthy guy, 28 yrs old who works at the bar of a very prominent hotel in this town. my openness & friendly nature does not work out well sometimes. men assume if you’re being nice it means.....there’s an open door policy for sex????????i agreed to have a drink wt this local guy who works at the fancy hotel where i was doing some research and development on various liquors & spirits for my current work. we had one drink at a nearby local bar and then he proceeded to walk me home to my hotel. then on the street as we got closer to my hotel he started grabbing me and kissing me and forcing himself on me groping my body. i had to get extremely fierce practically slap him and tell him this was absolutely unacceptable behavior & it was not until i yelled at him that i had been date raped in the past and did he want his girlfriend or sister or daughter or mother to go through this kind of thing that he stopped in shock at his own behavior and said he was sorry. thank god he then woke the fuck up, apologized and left. i am honestly so sick of men or people who deny that this is going on every day. i can’t even explain how many forms of this we deal with all the time. women of all ethnicities & social backgrounds. it does not discriminate. thank you so much @rosemcgowan for supporting me, believing me, & for standing up for all women against sexual assault & harassment. #metoo #notonemore #isaidno #wakethefuckup #fucktrump #timesup #equality #ibelieveher #sexualharassment #protect #support #fightback #originalgangster #hellno #texashuntress #sexgunsrocknroll

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
yesterday i cofacilitated a closed discussion for black women called "unpacking r. kelly." though it was in the aftermath of the documentary, we truly focused on the larger systems at play in our own experiences. i am so proud of the brave work we did in not only defining what sexual abuse has looked like for us but crafting a vision for the difference we would like to see going forward. i shared in my ig story yesterday that i love black people soooo much. i love us beyond the expectations that are in place that says that's just how it's always been. i love us enough to imagine a future that i have never seen but know in my bones is possible. this means asking the hard questions, sitting with the uncomfortable answers and doing some real reflection. i'm ready to make the ancestors proud and heal generational trauma for the sake of everyone in my lineage. stay tuned for a follow up event that is open to all genders. we will absolutely be keeping this conversation alive and engaging the community in this important work. thank you again to @soulzandgspotz and @alternativewaves for making this space possible. i'm so grateful for our paths crossing!

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

she claims to see “all points of view.” fans who attended erykah badu’s chicago concert were surprised by some of the singer’s choice of words during her set. badu, who is known to deliver wisdom as banter between songs, apparently defended r. kelly who is currently facing the consequences of resurfaced sexual abuse allegations. she was reportedly booed for this stance during her performance at the aragon ballroom.

one concert-goer tweeted: “i really want to say how much i loved erykah badu’s concert tonight. but i can’t get over how she tried to justify and defend r. kelly’s actions and reputation during her set… i’m so disappointed.”another attendee referred to what the songstress is believed to have said onstage: ‘“what if one of the people who was assaulted by r kelly becomes an offender? we gonna crucify them too?’ -erykah badu at her chicago concert.” badu seemed to refer to this situation in a caption attached to a picture she posted to instagram, previously. “having eyes that can see all points of view is a blessing … and a curse in the court of public opinion,” she wrote. “a mother i c on both sides like chanel.” a social media user commented, “i loved you until i realised you supported a rapist and paedophile as your brother.” the follower received a response shortly after: “correction, love has little to do with supporting others’ bad choices. love is wisdom,” badu stated. peep the receipts in the full story at www.itskenbarbie.com (or swipe) what do you guys think? #rkelly #survivingrkelly #robertkelly #metoo #muterkelly #lifetimetv #erykahbadu #erykah #badu #baduism #entertainment #entertainmentblog #entertainementnews #gossip

text:
la curiosidad mató al 😿(aunque murió más sabio 😼) no me sigas por algo malo, que el/la que siembra recoge 💞 tampoco lo hagas si eres menor.

si pinchas en este enlace y tiras hacia abajo un poquito, verás cómo me presenta la editorial mito: https://mitoeditorial.blogspot.com/p/autor-invitado.html 👋😹👍🐩💫
puedes leer artículos míos en diario alhaurín y en 101 málaga, así como en las revistas culturales guatiní (miami) y mimeógrafo (méxico). también me presentaron en la ventana del arte (la guía más completa sobre exposiciones en españa) y en webs y blogs como: munduky y repoelas (ambas españolas) y, en inglés, en art reveal magazine https://go.shr.lc/2u3tk4e 🍹🎻🦄💂 mis novelas llegan a cualquier lugar 🗺 desde: 
my novels arrive everywhere from

http://www.bubok.es/autores/bokusu

pincha el enlace en mi perfil.
verás que están en papel; que puedes leer las primeras páginas, algunas críticas y más... la 1ª también en formato digital. son para mayores de 18 años.

you can click the link in my profile. you'll see they are in paper, you can read the first pages, some critics and more... the first one is also for ebook, your computer, etc. they are for adults. 😘 
todo lo ocurrido desde que decidí publicar y más en: http://www.margaritabokusumina.blogspot.com

puedes seguirme también en youtube, fb (2 perfiles, uno más usado que el otro, y una página de autora), en twitter y soundcloud (otros 2 perfiles, uno de ellos con más de 30 grabaciones en español, inglés y francés macarrónico)

my novels arrive everywhere from

http://www.bubok.es/autores/bokusu

pincha el enlace en mi perfil.
verás que están en papel; que puedes leer las primeras páginas, algunas críticas y más... la 1ª también en formato digital. son para mayores de 18 años.

you can click the link in my profile. you'll see they are in paper, you can read the first pages, some critics and more... the first one is also for ebook, your computer, etc. they are for adults. 😘

puedes seguirme también en youtube, fb (2 perfiles, uno más usado que el otro, y una página de autora), en twitter y soundcloud (otros 2 perfiles, uno de ellos con más de 30 grabaciones en español, inglés y francés macarrónico)

text:
veli pasha’s page by louis dupré (1789–1837). veli pasha was the oldest son of ali pasha of ioannina, known for both his brutality and generosity (byron was his happy guest). ali pasha is known to have ordered a woman blamed for one of his sons' adultery sewn into a sack and drowned. byron retold this story many times, with varying degrees of his own involvement to embellish the tale. veli pasha (not the adulterer), like his father, was fond of boys. 39 or 40 at the time of byron's visit, veli called the poet "beautiful boy." 🐝

text:
what does #metoo❤️ mean to you?

for some, it means the awkward moment when we have to fend off unwanted advances, of a man. for others it’s being the only girl in a room full of inappropriate banter between inappropriate men. 
to some, it means something completely different. some women are destroyed mentally and physically by the person they loved and trusted most. these women are no different than you and i. they woke up, on their wedding day, with hopes and dreams of fairy tale endings. what happens when life becomes anything but a fairytale? where are we, as a society when these women need us the most? people who know me, know i almost never share these things, but this one hits so close to home that i have no choice, but to share with others! if everyone reading this gave as little as $5, this beautiful young mom could start to get her life back... think about that!  let’s remind her she is not alone and not forgotten! give what you can! thanks! link in bio. #metoo #metoomovement #putyourmoneywherehermouthis #abusesurvivor #abusedwomen

text:
this is a lot and and it’s pretty personal so if you read it - thank you.
.
i want to start by saying that not all men are actively creating this current harmful and degrading culture for women. i have many wonderful men in my life. and the #metoo movement and feminism need men to speak with us, because we are far more powerful together.
.
i want to share a few reasons why i march in support of #metoo and women’s rights:
1. i was assaulted while in college - i was not wearing a short skirt nor was i drunk - and this gives me a chance to publicly say #metoo and join the millions of voices around the world in solidarity so that the next nassar can’t leave a wake of unbelieved victims.
2. a history of injustice and a trajectory of the same globally for women in court rooms, child brides, humans being trafficked - people should be protected and treated with full respect regardless of gender, religion, sexual orientation, race...
3. we are not that far removed from illegal birth control for single women or men-only universities - and are not removed at all from people like nassar and weinstein using their influence and power to manipulate and hurt so many women
4. our country has elected a man as president - to the highest office of power and honor - who publicly admits (and brags) to having violated women as a result of his status. calling attention and paying attention is crucial.
.
there are so many reasons and these are just a few, but it truly is empowering to join the voices of friends and strangers alike to speak up for all people.
.
anita hill and christine blasey ford - 20 years apart, with the same familiar story. both sets of male dominated courts did not hear them. but we did. the same conclusion now does not mean the same old story. they were not believed. and yet the wake that they both created has changed so much. and they are reasons why we march - to continue raising awareness on the change that is still needed.
.
if you made it here, thanks so much for listening.
.
#metoo #womensmarch #womensmarch2019 #womensmarchnyc #nyc #imwithher

text:
la curiosidad mató al 😿(aunque murió más sabio 😼) no me sigas por algo malo, que el/la que siembra recoge 💞 tampoco lo hagas si eres menor.

si pinchas en este enlace y tiras hacia abajo un poquito, verás cómo me presenta la editorial mito: https://mitoeditorial.blogspot.com/p/autor-invitado.html 👋😹👍🐩💫
puedes leer artículos míos en diario alhaurín y en 101 málaga, así como en las revistas culturales guatiní (miami) y mimeógrafo (méxico). también me presentaron en la ventana del arte (la guía más completa sobre exposiciones en españa) y en webs y blogs como: munduky y repoelas (ambas españolas) y, en inglés, en art reveal magazine https://go.shr.lc/2u3tk4e 🍹🎻🦄💂 mis novelas llegan a cualquier lugar 🗺 desde: 
my novels arrive everywhere from

http://www.bubok.es/autores/bokusu

pincha el enlace en mi perfil.
verás que están en papel; que puedes leer las primeras páginas, algunas críticas y más... la 1ª también en formato digital. son para mayores de 18 años.

you can click the link in my profile. you'll see they are in paper, you can read the first pages, some critics and more... the first one is also for ebook, your computer, etc. they are for adults. 😘

puedes seguirme también en youtube, fb (2 perfiles, uno más usado que el otro, y una página de autora), en twitter y soundcloud (otros 2 perfiles, uno de ellos con más de 30 grabaciones en español, inglés y francés macarrónico)

text:
you can support survivors.
🤗
💜
one of the symptoms the traumatized individual experiences is negative changes in mood & thought or cognition. beliefs that you’re not safe, can’t trust, should have done something, or aren’t good enough affect your emotional state. when you hold beliefs like these, which are normal given a traumatic experience, they alter the mental filter through which everything flows. 🤯
🧠
it’s like having 💩 colored glasses. so, if you’re telling your traumatized loved one to just look at the bright side, to pull themselves up by their boot straps, or to just walk it off you’re not supporting them even if you’re intentions are in the right place. however, there are ways you can help.
😊
🙌🏻
things you can say or do:
🤝
1. you can tell them you love them & want to spend time with them.
2. you can offer to bring them food or take them to an appointment.
3. you can offer to sit silently with them just being a calming presence.
4. you can tell them you don’t have all the right words & aren’t sure how to help, but ask what they want or need.
5. you can tell them you know they probably don’t want to talk about it but if they ever did you’ve got working ears & a functional heart.
6. you can help them find resources if they’re interested or ready.
7. you can learn more about how trauma affects people so you can better understand how to support them.
8. you can tell them you’re going for a walk and would love for them to join if their able, knowing it’s not going to cure them but may add to their recovery process.
9. you can get consent to touch them especially if it was a sexual assault/abuse... even for a hug. and, that looks like “hey, you open for a hug?”
10. send a text to let them know you care even 2 weeks, 1 month, 3 months, & beyond in the days after the trauma. traumatized people can be affected even years later & don’t stop needing kindness after a marked period of time. also, this is a general rule for all people.
😁
💞

text:
la curiosidad mató al 😿(aunque murió más sabio 😼) no me sigas por algo malo, que el/la que siembra recoge 💞 tampoco lo hagas si eres menor.

si pinchas en este enlace y tiras hacia abajo un poquito, verás cómo me presenta la editorial mito: https://mitoeditorial.blogspot.com/p/autor-invitado.html 👋😹👍🐩💫
puedes leer artículos míos en diario alhaurín y en 101 málaga, así como en las revistas culturales guatiní (miami) y mimeógrafo (méxico). también me presentaron en la ventana del arte (la guía más completa sobre exposiciones en españa) y en webs y blogs como: munduky y repoelas (ambas españolas) y, en inglés, en art reveal magazine https://go.shr.lc/2u3tk4e 🍹🎻🦄💂 mis novelas llegan a cualquier lugar 🗺 desde: 
my novels arrive everywhere from

http://www.bubok.es/autores/bokusu

pincha el enlace en mi perfil.
verás que están en papel; que puedes leer las primeras páginas, algunas críticas y más... la 1ª también en formato digital. son para mayores de 18 años.

you can click the link in my profile. you'll see they are in paper, you can read the first pages, some critics and more... the first one is also for ebook, your computer, etc. they are for adults. 😘 
todo lo ocurrido desde que decidí publicar y más en: http://www.margaritabokusumina.blogspot.com

puedes seguirme también en youtube, fb (2 perfiles, uno más usado que el otro, y una página de autora), en twitter y soundcloud (otros 2 perfiles, uno de ellos con más de 30 grabaciones en español, inglés y francés macarrónico)

text: it took 8 years (a quarter of my life), 4 countries, and the me too movement to get our play produced in the art mecca of the world. in 2011, dominique strauss kahn sexually assaulted his chambermaid in the sofitel hotel in nyc. in 2012, my dad and i took his play to a private reading in a basement in paris followed by a run at the edinburgh fringe festival with a 4 star review in @thetimes we tried for the west end in london and off-broadway in nyc to no avail. we tried to turn it into a cle ethics credit, but not enough lawyers signed up to come on a tuesday night. six years later, we braved up and had another go - and this time, it was picked up and launched into production! danke dir berlin. you are brave and bold and most certainly the art capitol of the world! #metoo #metoomovement #playwright #theatre #bts #politicaltheatre #onlocation #onstage #producer #perseverance #riseup #shinealight #globalcitizen #fightthegoodfight #dsk #lawyer #womensmarch #togetherwerise #a21 #presidentialsuite #nyc #berlin
name: lizabinkley
tweet_full: it took 8 years (a quarter of my life), 4 countries, and the me too movement to get our play produced in the art mecca of the world. in 2011, dominique strauss kahn sexually assaulted his chambermaid in the sofitel hotel in nyc. in 2012, my dad and i took his play to a private reading in a basement in paris followed by a run at the edinburgh fringe festival with a 4 star review in @thetimes we tried for the west end in london and off-broadway in nyc to no avail. we tried to turn it into a cle ethics credit, but not enough lawyers signed up to come on a tuesday night. six years later, we braved up and had another go - and this time, it was picked up and launched into production! danke dir berlin. you are brave and bold and most certainly the art capitol of the world! #metoo #metoomovement #playwright #theatre #bts #politicaltheatre #onlocation #onstage #producer #perseverance #riseup #shinealight #globalcitizen #fightthegoodfight #dsk #lawyer #womensmarch #togetherwerise #a21 #presidentialsuite #nyc #berlin

text:
everyone says love yourself like it's this easy task.  when in fact, it's a battle. who knew identifying that you don't feel worthy could be so painful. or that feeling of inadequacy makes you find comfort in another person filling a void, regardless of how terrible they are to you. it took many years to realize what it meant to love myself. it's still a battle, especially in those times of frustration or triggers. when i learned to love myself, i learned to make more quality decisions for myself. i chose to put myself first, rather than accommodate everyone else. i learned to stop pushing people away who care and remove toxic people. 
i realized i spent too much time learning about others, and what they love and hate, than focusing on caring about what i love and hate. i choose to be my own best friend that looks out for me. i protect me. i love me. and, i know i am worthy. .
.
.
.
.
.

text: today was a beautiful day to reflect on the life of martin luther king jr. and consider where we are situated in history. sitting in duke chapel, which used to hold a statue of robert e lee, and taking a moment to feel pride for durham and the city’s decision to rehouse the confederate memorial - as-is - with a full explanation of how it came to be, and how it came to fall, and to consider the recent (successful!!) fight to remove silent sam from the unc campus... we have come a long way but still have at least as far to go. hearing tarana burke describe the birth of #metoo in the context of the civil rights movement highlights the intersection of all violence and oppression, and brings home for me the harmful and negative role that white women, and white feminism, have played in the lives of woc across history. we have so, so much work to do and we are not any one of us free until we all are free. 🙌🏽🙌🏽🙌🏽💖💖💖🙌🏽🙌🏽💖🙌🏽💖💖 #dukemlk

text:
2nd time read! .
last year was #gameon with the #metoo movement but it wasn't just about punishing offenders and making the world pay attention. 
what happens after? how do we get men to champion our cause at work? how do we debunk the notion that its all a witchhunt. how do we build a real partnership? .
it's all here, in the pages of this book. thanks to the lovely @adiatdisu for gifting it to me.
.
.
